Now that the Democrats are actively floating the idea of a coalition Speaker in exchange for legislative concessions, the rebels will likely want to declare victory and actualize their gains by giving McCarthy the job. He'll probably have to promote one of the rebels into leadership as a final act of contrition, meaning either Lisa McClain is out of her job as Secretary for the Majority or Richard Hudson is out as Chair of the NRCC. That would effectively give the Freedom Caucus a voting majority among the seven principal party officers which would help guarantee McCarthy's agreement against their fear of a backstab.

Representative McCarthy's attempt at becoming Speaker of the House is becoming increasingly more unattainable as the 7th round of voting occurs. At this time, Rep McCarthy will again be unable to reach the 218 votes required to secure the Speaker position. Last night's adjournment occurred after new offers were made to the 20 representatives who voted for Rep Donald; however, this did little to persuade his opposition as it appears he will be short the number of votes again after the seventh ballot.

As a non-American who spends time in USA and has “some” understanding of system (nothing like a born/raised American) this is some combination of bonkers and fascinating. I think it will be McCarthy since each vote he is leading. Also, Scalise is supporting McCarthy and asking colleagues to come together. I think they will elect a speaker prior to 21 Jan, because they can't do any business prior to electing a speaker, which means they can't get sworn in.

My approach was to first estimate a viable base rate. I looked at all the times when a multitude of votes was necessary to elect a house speaker. Based on a Washington Post article, I calculated the average needed votes in these cases to be 22,7. This number correlates closest to the 1816 election, which took 22 votes. Based on Wikipedia, the spot was vacant between march 3rd until december 5th for over 9 months. This election is of course not representative neither is taking the average from such a small sample size and I did not actually calculate the time it took on average but I have to work with something.

Never underestimate gridlock. McCarthy may eventually prevail, but it may take until after January 21st (apparently this process can drag on for weeks or even months, there is no time limit). The vast majority of Republicans seem to want McCarthy to become speaker or at least are willing to vote for him so far, it's just 20 extreme holdouts who are engaging in some political warfare or grandstanding or whatever this is. Jordan has stated he supports McCarthy.

What the Ds need to do, but won't, is announce that they will all vote for one of the surviving grownup Republicans. If they do that, and even a few Republicans support that person, it cuts the Trumpeter Swains right out. The Rs won the election and are entitled to a Speaker, but they're not required to go with a sock puppet of the President-Eject. If the Ds put an R in the Speakership, they will be able to make some deals for committee chairs--and more important, there will be a Speaker who will be inclined to work with them to get things done instead of spending two years presiding over a tantrum. This would be better for the country, and maybe for both parties, and so is out of the question.
